  "title": "Intellectual",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "16ecc5090cc61a67",
      "text": "Only in very complex societies does the mechanism of evolutionary [[Variation]] gain a high degree of independence, an almost role-like institutionalizability in the form of the intellectual. Intellectuals are to be located here in their function. They can be characterized by a relatively unbound – not bound by power and not even by truth – but nevertheless harmonious use of [[Language]]."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "38ad829190904869",
      "text": "The function of their harmonization services is limited to the variation mechanism, but for that very reason it overlaps all specific selector mechanisms. Truth, as we shall see in the next section, is only one of the selectors that enable com m unication success. The example of the \"critical\" intellectual confirms once again that the function of va riation, even in a highly differentiated form, still requires built-in harmonizations - albeit not ones that are identical to the mechanisms for selection and for stabilization."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "28dfa89deed3b2cc",
      "text": "Language and the normalization of its use only explain the possibility of relatively harmonious variation of expectation patterns. It is a second question in which direction a use of this possibility is probable. This [[Probability]] is co-determined by the fact that in all meaningful communication an anticipation of the reaction and counter-expectations of the other is unavoidable. Thus, unlike in organic [[Evolution]], an [[Anticipation]] of selection and stabilizability is built into the variation itself, and a second approach is needed to clarify that and how there is nevertheless excess variation and thus some difference in the mechanisms for [[Variation]], [[Selection]], and [[Stabilization]]. The problem, in other words, is how the variation mechanism of normalized language use is prevented from too accurately anticipating selection and stabilization."
    },
