      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "28dfa89deed3b2cc",
        "text": "Language and the normalization of its use only explain the possibility of relatively harmonious variation of expectation patterns. It is a second question in which direction a use of this possibility is probable. This probability is co-determined by the fact that in all meaningful communication an anticipation of the reaction and counter-expectations of the other is unavoidable. Thus, unlike in organic evo lution, an anticipation of selection and stabilizability is built into the variation itself, and a second approach is needed to clarify that and how there is nevertheless excess variation and thus some diffe rence in the mechanisms for variation, selection, and stabilization. The problem, in other words, is how the variation mechanism of normalized language use is prevented from too accurately anticipating selection and stabilization."
